    <text>
        <body>
            <div xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Tamás Szalaházy to Miklós Oláh (Bratislava, 27 February
                    1530)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">1. King John I almost occupied Eger as well; all the
                            unfaithful lords have gathered to besiege the castle. 2. Choron has
                            recovered the castle of Veszprém, while Tahy and Piskey have fled.
                            Esztergom was looted by the Spanish, while the Turkish sloops robbed the
                            chapter.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb facs="15300207_1_1.jpg"/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Idem Nicolao Olao.<note type="critic" xml:id="note.1">About his
                        letter, see <hi rend="smallcap">Békefi</hi> 1913, 11.</note></p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">[1.] Credo iam te certius cognovisse, quod nuper ignorabas, ut
                    exercitus regius retrocesserit etc. piget meminisse. Facis mentionem
                        <placeName>Agriae</placeName>,<note type="critic" xml:id="note.2">After 28
                        October, 1529, the army of Ferdinand I followed the withdrawing Turks and
                        occupied the castles of Western Hungary, even parts of Upper Hungary, as far
                        as the lines between Eger and Košice.</note> quae iampridem in hostium venit
                    potestatem, cum prius mensem unum et dies aliquot omnibus viribus equestribus,
                    pedestribus, quas habebat <persName>Ioannes</persName>,<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.3">King John I.</note> fuisset acerrime oppugnata et per meos
                    strenue item et fortiter defensa. <persName>Hieronimus Lasko</persName><note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.4">Hieronymus Łaski (1496–1541) was a Polish
                        aristocrat and diplomat. After Mohács, he entered King John I’s service and
                        became his legate to Paris, Coppenhagen, and Munich. He was King John I’s
                        most important diplomat, especially to the Sublime Porta. Between 1528–1531,
                        he was <hi rend="italic">ispán</hi> of Szepes county and Voivode of
                        Transylvania from 1530. Even though Łaski conspired with Gritti against King
                        John I, their plan was discovered, and Łaski became an ally and a diplomat
                        of King Ferdinand I.</note> cum Polonis, <persName>Cozka</persName><note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.5">Péter Koczka or his brother Miklós Koczka,
                        both were King John I’s loyal captains.</note> cum Bohaemis et tormentis
                    bellicis, <persName>Ioannes Tahy</persName>,<note type="critic" xml:id="note.6"
                        >János Tahy, Prior of Vrana, from 1525 Ban of Croatia, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Varga</hi> 2008, 1110.</note><persName> Ioannes
                        Zerechen</persName>,<note type="critic" xml:id="note.7">János Szerecsen
                        (†1532), <hi rend="italic">familiaris</hi> of the Szapolyai family, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Kubinyi</hi> 2008, 229.</note><persName>Caspar
                        Raskay</persName>,<note type="critic" xml:id="note.8">Gáspár Ráskay was a
                        Hungarian poet, and Chief Chamberlain of King Louis II. He participated in
                        the battle of Mohács, later he became loyal to King John I. For his merits,
                        King John I appointed him <hi rend="italic">ispán</hi> of Nógrád county,
                        later <hi rend="italic">ispán</hi> of Temes county, see [<hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Szilády</hi>] 1893.</note><persName>Petrus Bodo</persName>,<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.9">Péter Bodó.</note><persName>Thomas
                        Nadasdi</persName>, <persName>Pazthay</persName>,<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.10">He is either Zsigmond Pásztói or Ferenc Pásztói, son of
                        György Pásztói, possessors of Pásztó, see <hi rend="smallcap">Kubinyi</hi>
                        2000, 324–325.</note><persName>Puthmoky</persName>,<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.11">Imre Putnoki, former Master Cupbearer of King Louis II,
                        then King John I’s Marshal, and <hi rend="italic">ispán</hi> of Borsod
                        county.</note> denique omnis turba perfidorum ad illius arcis expugnationem
                    concurrerat.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.3">[2.] Vesprimiensis arx recuperata nuper fuit per <persName>Andream
                        Choron</persName> et alios familiares meos et mox per <persName>Ioannem <del
                            corresp="Olahus">Thagy</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                            >Thahy</add></persName>, <persName>Franciscum Somogy</persName>,<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.12">Probably Ferenc Somogyi of Endréd, <hi
                            rend="italic">viceispán</hi> of Somogy county. He was Captain of Tata
                        and Komárom until 1526.</note><persName>Petrum Emresy</persName>,<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.13">Péter Imreffy. In 1534, he occurs in Bálint
                        Török’s letter, see <hi rend="smallcap">Bessenyei</hi> 1994, 85 (Ep.
                        120).</note> et quosdam pedites Bohemos, et per aliquot millia rusticorum
                    fuit obsessa et oppugnata violentissime, sed Deo et fidelissimis castellanis
                    meis propugnantibus servata. Ioannes Tahy cum suis turpissime depulsus occisis
                    et vulneratis hominibus circiter quadringentis, amisso etiam fratre et plerisque
                    familiaribus; negant de Bohemis superfuisse decem, quin saucii fuerint aut
                    mortui. Erant et autem, ut intelligo, <del corresp="Olahus">trecentis</del><add
                        corresp="Olahus" type="corr">trecenti</add> de meis duo levissime vulnerati.
                        <persName>Piskey</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.14">We do not
                        know him more closely. The family possessed Piski in Bihar county and was
                        loyal to King John I, see <hi rend="smallcap">Csánki</hi> 1890, 638, and <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Jakó</hi> 1940, 324.</note> his diebus ad
                        <placeName>Ugrot</placeName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.15"
                        >Uhrovec.</note> per nostros est profligatus.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">Hispani civitatem Strigoniensem<note type="critic" xml:id="note.16"
                        >Esztergom.</note> nuper diripuerant. Turcarum nasadistae capitulum
                    diripuerunt, e civitate quicquid erat hominum abductum. Hic nulli fiunt
                    apparatus. Vale.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.5"><placeName>Posonii</placeName> 27. Februarii 1530.</p>
            </div>
